# React Component Structure

## Internal Order (Airbnb standard)

Every component must follow this exact order:

```typescript
// 1. Hooks (useNavigate, useState, custom hooks)
// 2. Local variables derived from hook data
// 3. useEffect (side effects)
// 4. Event handlers / derived functions
// 5. Early returns for loading/error states
// 6. Main return — always blank line before it

export const CustomerCard = ({ id, name }: CustomerCardProps) => {
  const navigate = useNavigate()
  const { data, isLoading, hasError } = useCustomerData(id)
  const { email, phone } = data ?? {}

  useEffect(() => {
    // side effect
  }, [id])

  const handleEdit = () => navigate(`/customers/${id}/edit`)

  if (isLoading) return <CustomerCardLoading />

  if (hasError) return <CustomerCardError />

  return (
    <div>
      <h2>{name}</h2>
    </div>
  )
}
```

## Rules

- ✅ Named exports only — no default exports for components
- ✅ Split components that exceed 150 lines into sub-components
- ✅ Use early returns for loading and error states — reduces nesting
- ✅ Always blank line before the final `return`
- ✅ `Loading` and `Error` state components must mirror the main component structure

## JSX Formatting

Single-line when no logic:
```typescript
export const Divider = () => <hr className="border-dema-200" />
```

Multi-line with parens when JSX spans multiple lines:
```typescript
export const CustomerCard = () => (
  <div>
    <CustomerHeader />
    <CustomerBody />
  </div>
)
```

## Function Spacing Rules

No blank line between hooks:
```typescript
// ✅
const navigate = useNavigate()
const { id } = useParams()
const { data } = useCustomerData(id)
```

Blank line between separate function declarations:
```typescript
// ✅
const handleSave = () => { ... }

const handleDelete = () => { ... }
```

Blank line before `useEffect`:
```typescript
const { data } = useCustomerData(id)

useEffect(() => { ... }, [])
```

## Early Return Placement

```typescript
// ✅ Single-line early return — no braces, no blank line before
if (isLoading) return <Spinner />

// ✅ Multi-line if block — return on its own line
if (!data) {
  console.warn('Missing data')
  return null
}

// ❌ Avoid nested else — use early returns instead
if (isLoading) {
  return <Spinner />
} else {
  return <div>{data.name}</div>
}
```

## When to Split a Component

Split when:
- Component exceeds 150 lines
- Component handles more than one responsibility (UI + data logic)
- JSX is deeply nested (more than 3 levels)
- A JSX block is repeated 2+ times
